            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Experience here (with `echo $COLUMNS => 120`):\r\n\r\n\r\n**NeoVim launched directly from terminal (`nvim`)**\r\n\r\n* In terminal, `tput cols` is 120.\r\n* NeoVim uses **full 120 columns**, but ...\r\n* `:! tput cols` => **80**, although `set columns?` => **120**\r\n\r\n\r\n**NeoVim launched from MUTT (as email reader/editor)**\r\n\r\n* NeoVim uses **only 72 columns** of width, but ...\r\n* `:! tput cols` => **80**, `set columns?` => **72**\r\n* `kill -SIGWINCH $nvim_pid` expands width to available space AND corrects `set columns?` to **120**\r\n\r\nThough this looks like a configuration issue, I am unable to find any corresponding configuration in neither Vim nor Mutt.\r\n\r\n**WORKAROUND** (in mutt configuration):\r\n\r\n    set editor = 'nvim -c \"set columns=`tput cols`\"'\r\n\r\n\r\n**Behaviour equally reproducible in these three terminals:**\r\n\r\n* st (`TERM=st-256color`)\r\n* zutty (`TERM=xterm-256color`)\r\n* alacritty (`TERM=screen-256color`)\r\n\r\n\r\nNVIM v0.10.1\r\n",
